<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-541-529  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 541 529.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Communications of the ACM  Oct 1990 v33 n10 pS8(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Association for Computing Machinery 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Extended terms for SIG officers. (Special Interest Groups' bylaws)(ACMemberNet supplement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT/><NOTE>Only Text is presented here; see printed issues for graphics.andO;</NOTE><TEXT>Extended Terms For SIG Officers Bylaw 7, Special Interest Groups, Section 5,structure and Management, states that the officers of a permanent SIG areelected by plurality vote of the SIG members for two-year terms beginningJuly 1 in odd-numbered years.andP;  At the end of a two-year term following anelection, an option may be exercised by the SIG Board to extend the term of aSIG's officers for an additional two years.andM;The decision to extend or not extend the term of a SIG's officers must bemade sufficiently early to allow an election (if it is to be held) to beconducted before July 1 of odd-numbered years.andP;  In accordance with policy,the SIG Board on August 13th voted to extend the terms of office for officers(elected in June 1989) of the following Special Interest Groups:andM;SIGBDP (Business Data Processing and Management), SIGCHI (Computer and HumanInteraction), SIGCPR (Computer Personnel Research), SIGDOC (SystemsDocumentation), SIGMOD (Management of Data), SIGNUM (Numerical Mathematics),SIGSOFT (Software Engineering).andM;Elections will be held for any of these SIGs if a petiotion requesting suchan election is brought by one percent of the members of the SIG.andP;  A petitionto initiate an election must be received at ACM Headquarters, Office ofPolicy andamp; Administration, by October 30, 1990.andP;  If you have any questionsregarding the petition process (e.g., number of signatures required for aparticular SIG, petition contents, etc.), contact Pat Ryan, director ofpolicy and administration, at ACM Headquarters: 212-869-7440.andO;</TEXT></DOC>